			<h3 class="first"><a href="#p2024">Artemis Aspect for C#?</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=2024&amp;sid=665fec9c4b1a7904836d782e90d8f066#p2024"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Mensagem" title="Mensagem" /></a>por <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=296&amp;sid=665fec9c4b1a7904836d782e90d8f066">planetarian</a></strong> &raquo; 22 Jan 2013, 03:21 </p>

			

			<div class="content">I'm looking for a way to specify components for systems to deal with using more granularity than currently available.<br /><br />Here's the scenario. I want to be able to use a system to render geometry to screen viewports using selectable camera objects.<br /><br />1) I have a CameraComponent, which sets the view frustrum/etc of a typical camera. There may be multiple entities acting as cameras in the scene.<br />2) I have a ViewportComponent, which specifies an active camera and defines the portion of the screen that camera will draw to.<br />3) I have objects with BasicGeometryComponent or some such; specifying basic shape/texture data.<br /><br />Currently, it seems systems are defined either by a list of required(!) components, or by tag. So, either my entities MUST contain all necessary components to be part of the system, or they MUST be tagged.<br />Without seeing any other way to have a system work with multiple types of entities, the only way I know to handle this scenario right now is to use TagSystem, and I must tag all entities that are to be handled by that system.<br />This creates the rather nasty scenario where a special tag will be needed for *any* system that will need to handle multiple component types. Unless I'm missing something, this seems somewhat... less than intuitive.<br /><br />In September of last year, however, the original Artemis framework gained an interesting feature: Aspects; methods of specifying more granular criteria for what components a system should deal with. In addition to the 'all' mentality of current systems, it also has 'one' and 'exclude'. By combining these Aspects, you can indeed get very picky about what sorts of entities your system gets to work with.<br /><br />Are there any plans on bringing this to the C# port? Alternatively, is there a better way to accomplish what I want to do?<br /><br />Thanks for your consideration and any advice you can offer. =)</div>

			

		</div>

		
			<dl class="postprofile" id="profile2024">
			<dt>
				<a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=296&amp;sid=665fec9c4b1a7904836d782e90d8f066">planetarian</a>
