		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p2046">Re: Artemis Aspect for C#?</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=2046&amp;sid=665fec9c4b1a7904836d782e90d8f066#p2046"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Mensagem" title="Mensagem" /></a>por <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=303&amp;sid=665fec9c4b1a7904836d782e90d8f066">Seismo</a></strong> &raquo; 23 Fev 2013, 15:09 </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>tpastor escreveu:</cite>Hi,<br /><br />what do you mean by chained entities</div></blockquote><br /><br />For e.g. entities which depend on each other. May the following sample will explain that better. May you have a game where many objects interact physical correct and you may stack 10 entities. So what should happen when you pull out one entity in the mid and what will happen when you change the order but not the entities and their relations? <br />In general you would expect that the entities which are close to that one you pull, will try to go along with it and those at the ends of this &quot;chain&quot; will stay at there current position until the stack collapse, right? <br />everithing is fine now, but now freeze, reload the map and try that again. All entities know each others relation, but the order changed. The result will look very strange.<br />So, the order is significantly important, in any case where you have 1+n relations between entities.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>tpastor escreveu:</cite>why we need to make it volatile or readonly.<br />The multithread aproaches works dividing in two ways<br />- or for each system, we create multiple threads and process its entities in paralell  (systems as processed serially, entities in a system are paralleled)</div></blockquote><br />Which does not make any sense until you follow my concerns about &quot;chained&quot; entities. In that case you may not be able to use this approach.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>tpastor escreveu:</cite>-or we proccess all systems of a specific layer in parallel (all entities of a system is processed serially, the systems are paralled)</div></blockquote><br />This seems to me is the most common approach<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>tpastor escreveu:</cite>why these dictionaries needs to be volatile ? (add or remove entities are delayed until next frame, they are processed serially also ...)</div></blockquote><br />be carefull  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_e_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /> , you may need access to the same entity twice or more from different threads, how will you prevent runtime errors here when you do not say the compiler which lists needs to be not optimised for multithreading? I guess you know what you are doing there - better than me! I just think about what <a href="http://www.drdobbs.com/cpp/volatile-the-multithreaded-programmers-b/184403766" class="postlink">Andrei Alexandrescu had to say about using volatile</a>.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>tpastor escreveu:</cite>The clear method is a good sugestion, i will consider adding it !!!</div></blockquote><br />I'll make a patch for that, use it already in my game.</div>

			

		</div>

		
