	<div id="p2047" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p2047">Re: Artemis Aspect for C#?</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=2047&amp;sid=665fec9c4b1a7904836d782e90d8f066#p2047"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Mensagem" title="Mensagem" /></a>por <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54&amp;sid=665fec9c4b1a7904836d782e90d8f066" style="color: #000066;" class="username-coloured">tpastor</a></strong> &raquo; 23 Fev 2013, 23:49 </p>

			

			<div class="content">about the volatile.<br /><br />i dont agree (or i did not understand it correctely)<br /><br />You are changing the Content of the dictionaries, not the dictionaries reference. (we also wont add or remove anything from it)<br />So there is no need for volatile there. (the dictionary is &quot;read only&quot; in the parallel phase of the processing)<br /><br />Sinceraly, i never made dependent entitites. Never though about this use case ...<br />When 2 entities need to exchange information, i prefer to use messages.<br />Explicity dependency creates &quot;coupling&quot; that is not good =P<br /><br />About the multthreading ...<br />There is no simple way (without tons of lock, mutexes ...) to isolate entities.<br />imagine 2 systems ...<br />one update the speed based on the position and another update the position based on time ...   in a multithreading ... shit will happen. <br />Our solution for this kind of problem are the  layers:<br />you add independent systems in the same layer (systems in each layer are executed in parallel) and dependent systems in separeted layer ...</div>

			<div id="sig2047" class="signature">PloobsEngine<br />Creator and Developer<br />ploobs.com.br/?page_id=1381</div>

		</div>

		
